# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: applescript
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:applescript/applescript] AppleScript is primarily a mechanism for driving Apple events – an inter-application communication (IAC) technology that exchanges data between and controls applications.
[src:applescript/applescript] Additionally, AppleScript supports basic calculations and text processing, and is extensible via scripting additions that add functions to the language.
[src:applescript/applescript] AppleScript is tightly bound to the Mac environment, similar to how Windows Script Host is bound to the Windows environment.
[src:applescript/applescript] In other words, AppleScript is not a general purpose scripting language like Python.
[src:applescript/applescript] One way that AppleScript is bound to the unique aspects of its environment is that it relies on applications to publish *dictionaries* of addressable objects and operations.
[src:applescript/applescript] As is typical of a command language, AppleScript is not designed to directly perform intensive processing.
[src:applescript/applescript] For example, a script cannot efficiently perform intensive math operations or complicated text processing.
[src:applescript/applescript] However, AppleScript can be used in combination with other tools and technologies which allows it to leverage more efficient programming contexts.
[src:applescript/applescript] The language has aspects of structured, procedural, object-oriented and natural language programming, but does not strictly conform to any of these paradigms.
[src:applescript/applescript] In the late 1980s, Apple considered using HyperCard's HyperTalk scripting language as the standard language for end-user development across the company and within its classic Mac OS operating system, and for interprocess communication between Apple and non-Apple products.
[src:applescript/applescript] HyperTalk could be used by novices to program a HyperCard stack.
[src:applescript/applescript] Apple engineers recognized that a similar, but more object-oriented scripting language could be designed to be used with any application, and the AppleScript project was born as a spin-off of a research effort to modernize the Macintosh as a whole and finally became part of System 7.
[src:applescript/applescript] AppleScript was released in October 1993 as part of System 7.1.1 (System 7 Pro, the first major upgrade to System 7).
[src:applescript/applescript] 3.2) was one of the first major software applications that supported AppleScript.
[src:applescript/applescript] This, in turn, led to AppleScript being widely adopted within the publishing and prepress world, often tying together complex workflows.
[src:applescript/applescript] This was a key factor in retaining the Macintosh's dominant position in publishing and prepress, even after QuarkXpress and other publishing applications were ported to Microsoft Windows.
[src:applescript/applescript] After some uncertainty about the future of AppleScript on Apple's next generation OS, the move to Mac OS X (around 2002) and its Cocoa frameworks greatly increased the usefulness and flexibility of AppleScript.
[src:applescript/applescript] Cocoa applications allow application developers to implement basic scriptability for their apps with minimal effort, broadening the number of applications that are directly scriptable.
[src:applescript/applescript] At the same time, the shift to the Unix underpinnings and AppleScript's ability to run Unix commands directly, with the `do shell script` command, allowed AppleScripts much greater control over the operating system itself.
[src:applescript/applescript] AppleScript Studio, released with Mac OS X 10.2 as part of Xcode, and later AppleScriptObjC framework, released in Mac OS X 10.6, allowed users to build Cocoa applications using AppleScript.
[src:applescript/applescript] In a 2006 article, *Macworld* included AppleScript among its rankings of Apple's 30 most significant products to date, placing it at #17.
[src:applescript/applescript] In a 2013 article for *Macworld*, veteran Mac software developer and commentator John Gruber concluded his reflection on "the unlikely persistence of AppleScript" by noting: "In theory, AppleScript could be much better; in practice, though, it's the best thing we have that works.
[src:applescript/applescript] In October 2016, longtime AppleScript product manager and automation evangelist Sal Soghoian left Apple when his position was eliminated "for business reasons".
[src:applescript/applescript] Veterans in the Mac community such as John Gruber and Andy Ihnatko generally responded with concern, questioning Apple's commitment to the developer community and pro users.
[src:applescript/applescript] For the time being, AppleScript remains one component of macOS automation technologies, along with Automator, Shortcuts, Services, and shell scripting.
[src:applescript/applescript] AppleScript was designed to be used as an accessible end-user scripting language, offering users an intelligent mechanism to control applications, and to access and modify data and documents.
[src:applescript/applescript] AppleScript uses Apple events, a set of standardized data formats that the Macintosh operating system uses to send information to applications, roughly analogous to sending XPath queries over XML-RPC in the world of web services.
[src:applescript/applescript] Apple events allow a script to work with multiple applications simultaneously, passing data between them so that complex tasks can be accomplished without human interaction.
[src:applescript/applescript] Tell the photo-editing application to save the changed image in a file in some different folder (by sending that application a *Save* and/or *Close* Apple event).
[src:applescript/applescript] Send the new file path (via another Apple event) to a text editor or web editor application.
[src:applescript/applescript] Tell that editor application to write a link for the photo into an HTML file.
[src:applescript/applescript] Repeat the above steps for an entire folder of images (hundreds or even thousands of photos).
[src:applescript/applescript] Upload the HTML file and folder of revised photos to a website, by sending Apple events to a graphical FTP client, by using built-in AppleScript commands, or by sending Apple events to Unix FTP utilities.
[src:applescript/applescript] For the user, hundreds or thousands of steps in multiple applications have been reduced to the single act of running the script, and the task is accomplished in much less time and with no possibility of random human error.
[src:applescript/applescript] A large complex script could be developed to run only once, while other scripts are used again and again.
[src:applescript/applescript] An application's scriptable elements are visible in the application's Scripting Dictionary (distributed as part of the application), which can be viewed in any script editor.
[src:applescript/applescript] Elements are generally grouped into *suites,* according to loose functional relationships between them.
[src:applescript/applescript] There are two basic kinds of elements present in any suite: classes and commands.
[src:applescript/applescript] All scriptable applications share a few basic commands and objects, usually called the Standard Suite—commands to open, close or save a file, to print something, to quit, to set data to variables—as well as a basic *application* object that gives the scriptable properties of the application itself.
[src:applescript/applescript] Many applications have numerous suites capable of performing any task the application itself can perform.
[src:applescript/applescript] In exceptional cases, applications may support plugins which include their own scripting dictionaries.
[src:applescript/applescript] AppleScript was designed with the ability to build scripts intuitively by recording user actions.
[src:applescript/applescript] Such AppleScript recordability has to be engineered into the app—the app must support Apple events and AppleScript recording; as Finder supports AppleScript recording, it can be useful for reference.
[src:applescript/applescript] When AppleScript Editor (Script Editor) is open and the Record button clicked, user actions for recordable apps are converted to their equivalent AppleScript commands and output to the Script Editor window.
[src:applescript/applescript] The resulting script can be saved and re-run to duplicate the original actions, or modified to be more generally useful.
[src:applescript/applescript] Whereas Apple events are a way to send messages into applications, AppleScript is a particular language designed to send Apple events.
[src:applescript/applescript] In keeping with the objective of ease-of-use for beginners, the AppleScript language is designed on the natural language metaphor, just as the graphical user interface is designed on the desktop metaphor.
[src:applescript/applescript] A well-written AppleScript should be clear enough to be read and understood by anyone, and easily edited.
[src:applescript/applescript] The language is based largely on HyperCard's HyperTalk language, extended to refer not only to the HyperCard world of cards and stacks, but also theoretically to any document.
[src:applescript/applescript] To this end, the AppleScript team introduced the AppleEvent Object Model (AEOM), which specifies the objects any particular application "knows".
[src:applescript/applescript] The heart of the AppleScript language is the use of terms that act as nouns and verbs that can be combined.
[src:applescript/applescript] For example, rather than a different verb to print a page, document or range of pages (such as printPage, printDocument, printRange), AppleScript uses a single "print" verb which can be combined with an object, such as a page, a document or a range of pages.
[src:applescript/applescript] Generally, AEOM defines a number of objects—like "document" or "paragraph"—and corresponding actions—like "cut" and "close".
[src:applescript/applescript] The system also defines ways to refer to properties of objects, so one can refer to the "third paragraph of the document 'Good Day'", or the "color of the last word of the front window".
[src:applescript/applescript] AEOM uses an application *dictionary* to associate the Apple events with human-readable terms, allowing the translation back and forth between human-readable AppleScript and bytecode Apple events.
[src:applescript/applescript] To discover what elements of a program are scriptable, dictionaries for supported applications may be viewed.
[src:applescript/applescript] AppleScript includes syntax for ordinal counting, "the first paragraph", as well as cardinal, "paragraph one".
[src:applescript/applescript] Likewise, the numbers themselves can be referred to as text or numerically, "five", "fifth" and "5" are all supported; they are synonyms in AppleScript.
[src:applescript/applescript] Also, the word "the" can legally be used anywhere in the script in order to enhance readability: it has no effect on the functionality of the script.
[src:applescript/applescript] A "Hello, World!" program can be written as a single line.
[src:applescript/applescript] The development tools below provide a programing environment for scripting with AppleScript – supporting composing, validating, compiling, running and debugging scripts.
[src:applescript/applescript] Some also provide for listing AppleScript dictionaries, saving scripts in a number of formats, syntax highlighting and inserting code snippets.
[src:applescript/applescript] in all earlier and later versions of macOS.
[src:applescript/applescript] Scripts are written in document editing windows where they can be compiled and run, and these windows contain various panes in which logged information, execution results, and other information is available for debugging purposes.
[src:applescript/applescript] Access to scripting dictionaries and prewritten code snippets is available through the application menus.
[src:applescript/applescript] A suite of tools from Apple for developing applications with features for editing scripts and creating standalone applications written in AppleScript.
[src:applescript/applescript] , stepping in and out of functions/subroutines, variable tracking, etc.
[src:applescript/applescript] Script Debugger also contains an advanced dictionary browser that allows the user to see the dictionary in action in real world situations.
[src:applescript/applescript] , for example, and see how the dictionary's terms apply to that document, making it easier to determine which parts of the dictionary to use.
[src:applescript/applescript] Script Debugger is not designed to create scripts with a GUI, other than basic alerts and dialogs, but is focused more on the coding and debugging of scripts.
[src:applescript/applescript] A third-party freeware/commercial IDE for AppleScript, itself written entirely in AppleScript.
[src:applescript/applescript] Smile is free, and primarily designed for AppleScript development.
[src:applescript/applescript] SmileLab is commercial software with extensive additions for numerical analysis, graphing, machine automation and web production.
[src:applescript/applescript] Smile and SmileLab use an assortment of different windows—AppleScript windows for running and saving full scripts, AppleScript terminals for testing code line-by-line, unicode windows for working with text and XML.
[src:applescript/applescript] Users can create complex interfaces—called dialogs—for situations where the built-in dialogs in AppleScript are insufficient.
[src:applescript/applescript] AppleScript Libraries aims for re-usable AppleScript components and supports built-in AppleScript dictionary (sdef).
[src:applescript/applescript] ASObjC Explorer 4 can be an external Xcode script editor, too.
[src:applescript/applescript] for creating AppleScript applications with graphic user interfaces.
[src:applescript/applescript] For development and ad hoc scenarios, a script can be run from a script editor, but to support automation a script must run without opening another application.
[src:applescript/applescript] , or from any other place where applications can be run.
[src:applescript/applescript] Using AppleScript folder actions, scripts can be launched when specific changes occur in folders (such as adding or removing files).
[src:applescript/applescript] from the contextual menu; the location of this command differs slightly in Mac OS X 10.6.x from earlier versions.
[src:applescript/applescript] This same action can be achieved with third-party utilities such as Hazel.
[src:applescript/applescript] —which can run AppleScripts on demand using key combinations.
[src:applescript/applescript] This system-wide menu provides access to AppleScripts from the macOS menu bar, visible no matter what application is running.
[src:applescript/applescript] (In addition, many Apple applications, some third-party applications, and some add-ons provide their own script menus.
[src:applescript/applescript] These may be activated in different ways, but all function in essentially the same manner.) Selecting a script in the script menu launches it.
[src:applescript/applescript] ; in prior versions of Mac OS X, it could be enabled from the AppleScript Utility application.
[src:applescript/applescript] When first enabled, the script menu displays a default library of fairly generic, functional AppleScripts, which can also be opened in Script Editor and used as examples for learning AppleScript.
[src:applescript/applescript] Scripts can be organized so that they only appear in the menu when particular applications are in the foreground.
[src:applescript/applescript] by using the osascript command line tool.
[src:applescript/applescript] The osascript tool can run compiled scripts (.scpt files) and plain text files (.applescript files—these are compiled by the tool at runtime).
[src:applescript/applescript] Script applications can be run using the Unix open command.
[src:applescript/applescript] Re-usable AppleScript modules (available since OS X Mavericks), written in AppleScript or AppleScriptObjC and saved as script files or bundles in certain locations, that can be called from other scripts.
[src:applescript/applescript] When saved as a bundle, a library can include an AppleScript dictionary (sdef) file, thus functioning like a scripting addition but written in AppleScript or AppleScriptObjC.
[src:applescript/applescript] A framework for attaching Cocoa interfaces to AppleScript applications, part of the Xcode package in Mac OS X 10.4 and 10.5, now deprecated in favor of AppleScriptObjC.
[src:applescript/applescript] A Cocoa development software framework, also called AppleScript/Objective-C or ASOC, part of the Xcode package since Mac OS X Snow Leopard.
[src:applescript/applescript] AppleScriptObjC allows AppleScripts to use Cocoa classes and methods directly.
[src:applescript/applescript] AppleScriptObjC can be used in all subsequent Mac OS X versions.
[src:applescript/applescript] A graphical, modular editing environment in which *workflows* are built up from *actions*.
[src:applescript/applescript] It is intended to duplicate many of the functions of AppleScript without the necessity for programming knowledge.
[src:applescript/applescript] Automator has an action specifically designed to contain and run AppleScripts, for tasks that are too complex for Automator's simplified framework.
[src:applescript/applescript] These background-only applications, packaged with macOS, are used to allow AppleScript to access features that would not normally be scriptable.
[src:applescript/applescript] Plug-ins for AppleScript developed by Apple or third parties.
[src:applescript/applescript] Variables are not strictly typed, and do not need to be declared.
[src:applescript/applescript] Variables can take any data type (including scripts and functions).
[src:applescript/applescript] A subroutines cannot be called directly from an application tell block.
[src:applescript/applescript] Using the same technique for scripting addition commands can reduce errors and improve performance.
[src:applescript/applescript] A script can define custom data types, or use one of the many built-in classes and objects which are provided by the language and tend to be recognized by scriptable applications.
[src:applescript/applescript] AppleScript supports compound statement code structure via either single or multiple line syntax.
[src:applescript/applescript] The multiple line syntax ends a code block with a phrase that like `end *keyword*` where *keyword* is the statement keyword at the start of the block.
[src:applescript/applescript] A script object is full object – encapsulating methods and data and inheriting data and behavior from a parent script.
[src:applescript/applescript] Script objects can use the same 'tell' constructs that are used for application objects and can be loaded from and saved to files.
[src:applescript/applescript] Runtime performance can be enhanced in some cases by using script objects.
[src:applescript/applescript] The loop construct has multiple variations, all using the keyword **repeat**.
[src:applescript/applescript] The loop can be exited via **exit repeat**.
[src:applescript/applescript] For **repeat while**, the block is executed as long as a condition evaluates to true.
[src:applescript/applescript] The **repeat until** loop is the same except that the block is executed as long as the condition evaluates to false.
[src:applescript/applescript] A variable is initialized to a value and after each execution of the block, the variable is incremented by the step value; 1 if not specified.
[src:applescript/applescript] A variable has the value of each list item as the loop progresses.
[src:applescript/applescript] A **handler**, a variation of the block structure defines a subroutine.
[src:applescript/applescript] Handlers can also be defined using "to" in place of "on" and can be written to accept labeled parameters, not enclosed in parens.
[src:applescript/applescript] There are four types of predefined handlers in AppleScript—run, open, idle, and quit—each of which is created in the same way as the run handler shown above.
[src:applescript/applescript] Defines the main code of the script, which is called when the script is run.
[src:applescript/applescript] Run handler blocks are optional, unless arguments are being passed to the script.
[src:applescript/applescript] If an explicit run handler block is omitted, then all code that is not contained inside handler blocks is executed as though it were in an implicit run handler.
[src:applescript/applescript] When a script containing an "open handler' is saved as an applet, the applet becomes a droplet.
[src:applescript/applescript] A droplet can be identified in the Finder by its icon, which includes an arrow, indicating items can be dropped onto the icon.
[src:applescript/applescript] The droplet's open handler is executed when files or folders are dropped onto droplet's icon.
[src:applescript/applescript] References to the items dropped on the droplet's icon are passed to the droplet's script as the parameter of the open handler.
[src:applescript/applescript] A droplet can also be launched the same way as an ordinary applet, executing its run handler.
[src:applescript/applescript] A subroutine that is run periodically by the system when the application is idle.
[src:applescript/applescript] An idle handler can be used in applets or droplets saved as stay-open applets, and is useful for scripts that watch for particular data or events.
[src:applescript/applescript] The length of the idle time is 30 seconds by default, but can be changed by including a 'return x' statement at the end of the subroutine, where x is the number of seconds the system should wait before running the handler again.
[src:applescript/applescript] A handler that is run when the applet receives a Quit request.
[src:applescript/applescript] This can be used to save data or do other ending tasks before quitting.
[src:applescript/applescript] A comment can be formatted various ways.
[src:applescript/applescript] A line comment begins with `--` or alternatively in later versions (AppleScript 2.0, first released in Mac OS X Leopard) with `#`.
[src:applescript/applescript] The latter permits an AppleScript script to run as an executable if it begins with a shebang line `#!/usr/bin/osascript`.
[src:applescript/applescript] A block comment (can be multiple lines) is delimited by `(*` and `*)`.
[src:applescript/applescript] AppleScript has several user interface options, including dialogs, alerts, and list of choices.
[src:applescript/applescript] Each user interaction method can return the values of buttons clicked, items chosen or text entered for further processing.
[src:applescript/applescript] Apple provides the **Open Scripting Architecture** (OSA) for other scripting languages and third-party scripting/automation products (such as QuicKeys and UserLand Frontier) to function on an equal status with AppleScript.
[src:applescript/applescript] AppleScript is implemented as a component of Component Manager, and the basic specs for interfacing such components to the OSA are public, allowing other developers to add their own scripting components to the system.
[src:applescript/applescript] Public client APIs for loading, saving and compiling scripts work the same for all such components, which means that applets and droplets can hold scripts in any of those scripting languages.
[src:applescript/applescript] One feature of the OSA is scripting additions, or OSAX for *Open Scripting Architecture eXtension*, which were inspired by HyperCard's External Commands.
[src:applescript/applescript] Scripting additions are libraries that allow programmers to extend the function of AppleScript.
[src:applescript/applescript] Commands included as scripting additions are available system-wide, and are not dependent on an application (see also § AppleScript Libraries).
[src:applescript/applescript] The AppleScript Editor is also able to directly edit and run some of the OSA languages.
[src:applescript/applescript] JXA also provides an Objective-C (and C language) foreign language interface.
[src:applescript/applescript] Being an environment based on WebKit's JavaScriptCore engine, the JavaScript feature set is in sync with the system Safari browser engine.
[src:applescript/applescript] JXA provides a JavaScript module system and it is also possible to use CommonJS modules via browserify.
[src:applescript/aslr-intro] This document is a guide to the AppleScript language—its lexical conventions, syntax, keywords, and other elements.
[src:applescript/aslr-intro] It is intended primarily for use with AppleScript 2.0 or later and macOS version 10.5 or later.
[src:applescript/aslr-intro] AppleScript 2.0 can use scripts developed for any version of AppleScript from 1.1 through 1.10.7, any scripting addition created for AppleScript 1.5 or later for macOS, and any scriptable application for Mac OS v7.1 or later.
[src:applescript/aslr-intro] A script created with AppleScript 2.0 can be used by any version of AppleScript back to version 1.1, provided it does not use features of AppleScript, scripting additions, or scriptable applications that are unavailable in that version.
[src:applescript/aslr-intro] AppleScript is a scripting language created by Apple.
[src:applescript/aslr-intro] It allows users to directly control scriptable Macintosh applications, as well as parts of macOS itself.
[src:applescript/aslr-intro] You can create scripts—sets of written instructions—to automate repetitive tasks, combine features from multiple scriptable applications, and create complex workflows.
[src:applescript/aslr-intro] A scriptable application is one that can be controlled by a script.
[src:applescript/aslr-intro] For AppleScript, that means being responsive to interapplication messages, called *Apple events*, sent when a script command targets the application.
[src:applescript/aslr-intro] AppleScript itself provides a very small number of commands, but it provides a framework into which you can plug many task-specific commands—those provided by scriptable applications and scriptable parts of macOS.
[src:applescript/aslr-intro] Most script samples and script fragments in this guide use scriptable features of the Finder application, scriptable parts of macOS, or scriptable applications distributed with macOS, such as TextEdit (located in `/Applications`).
[src:applescript/aslr-intro] You should use this document if you write or modify AppleScript scripts, or if you create scriptable applications and need to know how scripts should work.
[src:applescript/aslr-intro] This guide describes the AppleScript language in a series of chapters and appendixes.
[src:applescript/aslr-intro] Glossary terms are shown in *boldface* where they are defined.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Automation includes the use of various equipment and control systems such as machinery, processes in factories, boilers, and heat-treating ovens, switching on telephone networks, steering, stabilization of ships, aircraft and other applications and vehicles with reduced human intervention.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Examples range from a household thermostat controlling a boiler to a large industrial control system with tens of thousands of input measurements and output control signals.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] In the simplest type of an automatic control loop, a controller compares a measured value of a process with a desired set value and processes the resulting error signal to change some input to the process, in such a way that the process stays at its set point despite disturbances.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] This closed-loop control is an application of negative feedback to a system.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The mathematical basis of control theory began in the 18th century and advanced rapidly in the 20th.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The term *automation*, inspired by the earlier word *automatic* (coming from *automaton*), was not widely used before 1947, when Ford established an automation department.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] It was during this time that the industry was rapidly adopting feedback controllers, Technological advancements introduced in the 1930s revolutionized various industries significantly.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The World Bank's World Development Report of 2019 shows evidence that the new industries and jobs in the technology sector outweigh the economic effects of workers being displaced by automation.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Job losses and downward mobility blamed on automation have been cited as one of many factors in the resurgence of nationalist, protectionist and populist politics in the US, UK and France, among other countries since the 2010s.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] It was a preoccupation of the Greeks and Arabs (in the period between about 300 BC and about 1200 AD) to keep an accurate track of time.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] In Ptolemaic Egypt, about 270 BC, Ctesibius described a float regulator for a water clock, a device not unlike the ball and cock in a modern flush toilet.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] This was the earliest feedback-controlled mechanism.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The appearance of the mechanical clock in the 14th century made the water clock and its feedback control system obsolete.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The Persian Banū Mūsā brothers, in their *Book of Ingenious Devices* (850 AD), described a number of automatic controls.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Two-step level controls for fluids, a form of discontinuous variable structure controls, were developed by the Banu Musa brothers.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] They also described a feedback controller.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The design of feedback control systems up through the Industrial Revolution was by trial-and-error, together with a great deal of engineering intuition.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] It was not until the mid-19th century that the stability of feedback control systems was analyzed using mathematics, the formal language of automatic control theory.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The centrifugal governor was invented by Christiaan Huygens in the seventeenth century, and used to adjust the gap between millstones.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Another control mechanism was used to tent the sails of windmills.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Also in 1745, Jacques de Vaucanson invented the first automated loom.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Around 1800, Joseph Marie Jacquard created a punch-card system to program looms.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] In 1771 Richard Arkwright invented the first fully automated spinning mill driven by water power, known at the time as the water frame.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] An automatic flour mill was developed by Oliver Evans in 1785, making it the first completely automated industrial process.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Bunce of England in 1784 as part of a model steam crane.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The centrifugal governor was adopted by James Watt for use on a steam engine in 1788 after Watt's partner Boulton saw one at a flour mill Boulton & Watt were building.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The governor could not actually hold a set speed; the engine would assume a new constant speed in response to load changes.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The governor was able to handle smaller variations such as those caused by fluctuating heat load to the boiler.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Also, there was a tendency for oscillation whenever there was a speed change.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] As a consequence, engines equipped with this governor were not suitable for operations requiring constant speed, such as cotton spinning.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Several improvements to the governor, plus improvements to valve cut-off timing on the steam engine, made the engine suitable for most industrial uses before the end of the 19th century.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Advances in the steam engine stayed well ahead of science, both thermodynamics and control theory.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The governor received relatively little scientific attention until James Clerk Maxwell published a paper that established the beginning of a theoretical basis for understanding control theory.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Relay logic was introduced with factory electrification, which underwent rapid adaptation from 1900 through the 1920s.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Central electric power stations were also undergoing rapid growth and the operation of new high-pressure boilers, steam turbines and electrical substations created a great demand for instruments and controls.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Central control rooms became common in the 1920s, but as late as the early 1930s, most process controls were on-off.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Operators typically monitored charts drawn by recorders that plotted data from instruments.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] To make corrections, operators manually opened or closed valves or turned switches on or off.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Control rooms also used color-coded lights to send signals to workers in the plant to manually make certain changes.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The development of the electronic amplifier during the 1920s, which was important for long-distance telephony, required a higher signal-to-noise ratio, which was solved by negative feedback noise cancellation.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] This and other telephony applications contributed to the control theory.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] In the 1940s and 1950s, German mathematician Irmgard Flügge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic controls, which found military applications during the Second World War to fire control systems and aircraft navigation systems.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Controllers, which were able to make calculated changes in response to deviations from a set point rather than on-off control, began being introduced in the 1930s.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Controllers allowed manufacturing to continue showing productivity gains to offset the declining influence of factory electrification.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Factory productivity was greatly increased by electrification in the 1920s.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Alexander Field notes that spending on non-medical instruments increased significantly from 1929 to 1933 and remained strong thereafter.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The First and Second World Wars saw major advancements in the field of mass communication and signal processing.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Other key advances in automatic controls include differential equations, stability theory and system theory (1938), frequency domain analysis (1940), ship control (1950), and stochastic analysis (1941).
[src:applescript/automation-p01] In 1959 Texaco's Port Arthur Refinery became the first chemical plant to use digital control.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Conversion of factories to digital control began to spread rapidly in the 1970s as the price of computer hardware fell.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The automatic telephone switchboard was introduced in 1892 along with dial telephones.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] By 1929, 31.9% of the Bell system was automatic.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Automatic telephone switching originally used vacuum tube amplifiers and electro-mechanical switches, which consumed a large amount of electricity.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Call volume eventually grew so fast that it was feared the telephone system would consume all electricity production, prompting Bell Labs to begin research on the transistor.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The logic performed by telephone switching relays was the inspiration for the digital computer.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The first commercially successful glass bottle-blowing machine was an automatic model introduced in 1905.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The machine, operated by a two-man crew working 12-hour shifts, could produce 17,280 bottles in 24 hours, compared to 2,880 bottles made by a crew of six men and boys working in a shop for a day.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The cost of making bottles by machine was 10 to 12 cents per gross compared to $1.80 per gross by the manual glassblowers and helpers.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Sectional electric drives were developed using control theory.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Sectional electric drives are used on different sections of a machine where a precise differential must be maintained between the sections.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] In steel rolling, the metal elongates as it passes through pairs of rollers, which must run at successively faster speeds.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] In paper making paper, the sheet shrinks as it passes around steam-heated drying arranged in groups, which must run at successively slower speeds.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The first application of a sectional electric drive was on a paper machine in 1919.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] One of the most important developments in the steel industry during the 20th century was continuous wide strip rolling, developed by Armco in 1928.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Before automation, many chemicals were made in batches.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] In 1930, with the widespread use of instruments and the emerging use of controllers, the founder of Dow Chemical Co. was advocating continuous production.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Self-acting machine tools that displaced hand dexterity so they could be operated by boys and unskilled laborers were developed by James Nasmyth in the 1840s.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Machine tools were automated with Numerical control (NC) using punched paper tape in the 1950s.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] This soon evolved into computerized numerical control (CNC).
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Today extensive automation is practiced in practically every type of manufacturing and assembly process.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Robots are especially useful in hazardous applications like automobile spray painting.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Robots are also used to assemble electronic circuit boards.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Automotive welding is done with robots and automatic welders are used in applications like pipelines.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] With the advent of the space age in 1957, controls design, particularly in the United States, turned away from the frequency-domain techniques of classical control theory and backed into the differential equation techniques of the late 19th century, which were couched in the time domain.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] During the 1940s and 1950s, German mathematician Irmgard Flugge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic control, which became widely used in hysteresis control systems such as navigation systems, fire-control systems, and electronics.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Through Flugge-Lotz and others, the modern era saw time-domain design for nonlinear systems (1961), navigation (1960), optimal control and estimation theory (1962), nonlinear control theory (1969), digital control and filtering theory (1974), and the personal computer (1983).
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Perhaps the most cited advantage of automation in industry is that it is associated with faster production and cheaper labor costs.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Another benefit could be that it replaces hard, physical, or monotonous work.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Additionally, tasks that take place in hazardous environments or that are otherwise beyond human capabilities can be done by machines, as machines can operate even under extreme temperatures or in atmospheres that are radioactive or toxic.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] They can also be maintained with simple quality checks.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] However, at the time being, not all tasks can be automated, and some tasks are more expensive to automate than others.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Initial costs of installing the machinery in factory settings are high, and failure to maintain a system could result in the loss of the product itself.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Automation primarily describes machines replacing human action, but it is also loosely associated with mechanization, machines replacing human labor.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The paradox of automation says that the more efficient the automated system, the more crucial the human contribution of the operators.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Humans are less involved, but their involvement becomes more critical.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Lisanne Bainbridge, a cognitive psychologist, identified these issues notably in her widely cited paper "Ironies of Automation." If an automated system has an error, it will multiply that error until it is fixed or shut down.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] A fatal example of this was Air France Flight 447, where a failure of automation put the pilots into a manual situation they were not prepared for.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Many roles for humans in industrial processes presently lie beyond the scope of automation.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Human-level pattern recognition, language comprehension, and language production ability are well beyond the capabilities of modern mechanical and computer systems (but see *Watson computer*).
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Tasks requiring subjective assessment or synthesis of complex sensory data, such as scents and sounds, as well as high-level tasks such as strategic planning, currently require human expertise.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] In many cases, the use of humans is more cost-effective than mechanical approaches even where the automation of industrial tasks is possible.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Therefore, algorithmic management as the digital rationalization of human labor instead of its substitution has emerged as an alternative technological strategy.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Overcoming these obstacles is a theorized path to post-scarcity economics.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] As of 2025-2026, real-world deployment of advanced robotics has revealed critical infrastructure limitations, such as "battery-life bottlenecks" (typically 2–4 hours of operation per charge) and the requirement for high-bandwidth Wi-Fi and specialized flooring for reliable function.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Additionally, robots continue to struggle with unpredictable human-made obstructions, which still necessitate human intervention to maintain operational flow.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Increased automation often causes workers to feel anxious about losing their jobs as technology renders their skills or experience unnecessary.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Early in the Industrial Revolution, when inventions like the steam engine were making some job categories expendable, workers forcefully resisted these changes.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Luddites, for instance, were English textile workers who protested the introduction of weaving machines by destroying them.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] More recently, some residents of Chandler, Arizona, have slashed tires and pelted rocks at a self-driving car, in protest over the cars' perceived threat to human safety and job prospects.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The relative anxiety about automation reflected in opinion polls seems to correlate closely with the strength of organized labor in that region or nation.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] According to one estimate, 47% of all current jobs in the US have the potential to be fully automated by 2033.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Furthermore, wages and educational attainment appear to be strongly negatively correlated with an occupation's risk of being automated.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Erik Brynjolfsson and Andrew McAfee argue that "there's never been a better time to be a worker with special skills or the right education, because these people can use technology to create and capture value.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Research by Carl Benedikt Frey and Michael Osborne of the Oxford Martin School argued that employees engaged in "tasks following well-defined procedures that can easily be performed by sophisticated algorithms" are at risk of displacement, and 47% of jobs in the US were at risk.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The study, released as a working paper in 2013 and published in 2017, predicted that automation would put low-paid physical occupations most at risk, by surveying a group of colleagues on their opinions.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] However, according to a study published in *McKinsey Quarterly* in 2015 the impact of computerization in most cases is not the replacement of employees but the automation of portions of the tasks they perform.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The methodology of the McKinsey study has been heavily criticized for being intransparent and relying on subjective assessments.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The methodology of Frey and Osborne has been subjected to criticism, as lacking evidence, historical awareness, or credible methodology.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Additionally, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) found that across the 21 OECD countries, 9% of jobs are automatable.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Based on a formula by Gilles Saint-Paul, an economist at Toulouse 1 University, the demand for unskilled human capital declines at a slower rate than the demand for skilled human capital increases.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] In the long run and for society as a whole it has led to cheaper products, lower average work hours, and new industries forming (i.e., robotics industries, computer industries, design industries).
[src:applescript/automation-p01] These new industries provide many high salary skill-based jobs to the economy.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] By 2030, between 3 and 14 percent of the global workforce will be forced to switch job categories due to automation eliminating jobs in an entire sector.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] While the number of jobs lost to automation is often offset by jobs gained from technological advances, the same type of job loss is not the same one replaced and that leading to increasing unemployment in the lower-middle class.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] This occurs largely in the US and developed countries where technological advances contribute to higher demand for highly skilled labor but demand for middle-wage labor continues to fall.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Economists call this trend "income polarization" where unskilled labor wages are driven down and skilled labor is driven up and it is predicted to continue in developed economies.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Lights-out manufacturing is a production system with no human workers, to eliminate labor costs.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] It grew in popularity in the U.S. when General Motors in 1982 implemented humans "hands-off" manufacturing to "replace risk-averse bureaucracy with automation and robots".
[src:applescript/automation-p01] However, the factory never reached full "lights out" status.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The costs of automation to the environment are different depending on the technology, product or engine automated.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] There are automated engines that consume more energy resources from the Earth in comparison with previous engines and vice versa.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Hazardous operations, such as oil refining, the manufacturing of industrial chemicals, and all forms of metal working, were always early contenders for automation.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The automation of vehicles could prove to have a substantial impact on the environment, although the nature of this impact could be beneficial or harmful depending on several factors.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Because automated vehicles are much less likely to get into accidents compared to human-driven vehicles, some precautions built into current models (such as anti-lock brakes or laminated glass) would not be required for self-driving versions.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Removal of these safety features reduces the weight of the vehicle, and coupled with more precise acceleration and braking, as well as fuel-efficient route mapping, can increase fuel economy and reduce emissions.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Despite this, some researchers theorize that an increase in the production of self-driving cars could lead to a boom in vehicle ownership and usage, which could potentially negate any environmental benefits of self-driving cars if they are used more frequently.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Automation of homes and home appliances is also thought to impact the environment.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] This study, along with others, indicated that the smart home's ability to monitor and adjust consumption levels would reduce unnecessary energy usage.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] However, some research suggests that smart homes might not be as efficient as non-automated homes.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] A more recent study has indicated that, while monitoring and adjusting consumption levels do decrease unnecessary energy use, this process requires monitoring systems that also consume an amount of energy.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The energy required to run these systems sometimes negates their benefits, resulting in little to no ecological benefit.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Another major shift in automation is the increased demand for flexibility and convertibility in manufacturing processes.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Manufacturers are increasingly demanding the ability to easily switch from manufacturing Product A to manufacturing Product B without having to completely rebuild the production lines.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Flexibility and distributed processes have led to the introduction of Automated Guided Vehicles with Natural Features Navigation.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Former analog-based instrumentation was replaced by digital equivalents which can be more accurate and flexible, and offer greater scope for more sophisticated configuration, parametrization, and operation.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] This was accompanied by the fieldbus revolution which provided a networked (i.e. a single cable) means of communicating between control systems and field-level instrumentation, eliminating hard-wiring.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Discrete manufacturing plants adopted these technologies fast.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The more conservative process industries with their longer plant life cycles have been slower to adopt and analog-based measurement and control still dominate.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The growing use of Industrial Ethernet on the factory floor is pushing these trends still further, enabling manufacturing plants to be integrated more tightly within the enterprise, via the internet if necessary.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Global competition has also increased demand for Reconfigurable Manufacturing Systems.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Engineers can now have numerical control over automated devices.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The result has been a rapidly expanding range of applications and human activities.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Computer-aided technologies (or CAx) now serve as the basis for mathematical and organizational tools used to create complex systems.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Notable examples of CAx include computer-aided design (CAD software) and computer-aided manufacturing (CAM software).
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The improved design, analysis, and manufacture of products enabled by CAx has been beneficial for industry.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Information technology, together with industrial machinery and processes, can assist in the design, implementation, and monitoring of control systems.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] One example of an industrial control system is a programmable logic controller (PLC).
[src:applescript/automation-p01] PLCs are specialized hardened computers which are frequently used to synchronize the flow of inputs from (physical) sensors and events with the flow of outputs to actuators and events.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Human-machine interfaces (HMI) or computer human interfaces (CHI), formerly known as *man-machine interfaces*, are usually employed to communicate with PLCs and other computers.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Service personnel who monitor and control through HMIs can be called by different names.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] In the industrial process and manufacturing environments, they are called operators or something similar.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] In boiler houses and central utility departments, they are called *stationary engineers*.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Host simulation software (HSS) is a commonly used testing tool that is used to test the equipment software.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] HSS is used to test equipment performance concerning factory automation standards (timeouts, response time, processing time).
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Cognitive automation, as a subset of AI, is an emerging genus of automation enabled by cognitive computing.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Its primary concern is the automation of clerical tasks and workflows that consist of structuring unstructured data.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Cognitive automation relies on multiple disciplines: natural language processing, real-time computing, machine learning algorithms, big data analytics, and evidence-based learning.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Artificially intelligent computer-aided design (CAD) can use text-to-3D, image-to-3D, and video-to-3D to automate in 3D modeling.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] AI CAD libraries could also be developed using linked open data of schematics and diagrams.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Ai CAD assistants are used as tools to help streamline workflow.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Technologies like solar panels, wind turbines, and other renewable energy sources—together with smart grids, micro-grids, battery storage—can automate power production.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Many agricultural operations are automated with machinery and equipment to improve their diagnosis, decision-making and/or performing.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Agricultural automation can relieve the drudgery of agricultural work, improve the timeliness and precision of agricultural operations, raise productivity and resource-use efficiency, build resilience, and improve food quality and safety.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Increased productivity can free up labour, allowing agricultural households to spend more time elsewhere.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The technological evolution in agriculture has resulted in progressive shifts to digital equipment and robotics.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Motorized mechanization using engine power automates the performance of agricultural operations such as ploughing and milking.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] With digital automation technologies, it also becomes possible to automate diagnosis and decision-making of agricultural operations.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] For example, autonomous crop robots can harvest and seed crops, while drones can gather information to help automate input application.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Motorized mechanization has generally increased in recent years.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa is the only region where the adoption of motorized mechanization has stalled over the past decades.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Automation technologies are increasingly used for managing livestock, though evidence on adoption is lacking.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Adoption is likely mostly in Northern Europe, and likely almost absent in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Automated feeding machines for both cows and poultry also exist, but data and evidence regarding their adoption trends and drivers is likewise scarce.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Many supermarkets and even smaller stores are rapidly introducing self-checkout systems reducing the need for employing checkout workers.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] In the U.S., the retail industry employs 15.9 million people as of 2017 (around 1 in 9 Americans in the workforce).
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Globally, an estimated 192 million workers could be affected by automation according to research by Eurasia Group.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Online shopping could be considered a form of automated retail as the payment and checkout are through an automated online transaction processing system, with the share of online retail accounting jumping from 5.1% in 2011 to 8.3% in 2016.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] However, two-thirds of books, music, and films are now purchased online.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] In addition, automation and online shopping could reduce demands for shopping malls, and retail property, which in the United States is currently estimated to account for 31% of all commercial property or around 7 billion square feet (650 million square metres).
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Amazon has gained much of the growth in recent years for online shopping, accounting for half of the growth in online retail in 2016.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Other forms of automation can also be an integral part of online shopping, for example, the deployment of automated warehouse robotics such as that applied by Amazon using Kiva Systems.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The food retail industry has started to apply automation to the ordering process; McDonald's has introduced touch screen ordering and payment systems in many of its restaurants, reducing the need for as many cashier employees.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The University of Texas at Austin has introduced fully automated cafe retail locations.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Some cafes and restaurants have utilized mobile and tablet "apps" to make the ordering process more efficient by customers ordering and paying on their device.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Some restaurants have automated food delivery to tables of customers using a conveyor belt system.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The use of robots is sometimes employed to replace waiting staff.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Automation in construction is the combination of methods, processes, and systems that allow for greater machine autonomy in construction activities.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Construction automation may have multiple goals, including but not limited to, reducing jobsite injuries, decreasing activity completion times, and assisting with quality control and quality assurance.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Automated mining involves the removal of human labor from the mining process.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The mining industry is currently in the transition towards automation.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Currently, it can still require a large amount of human capital, particularly in the third world where labor costs are low so there is less incentive for increasing efficiency through automation.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) started the research and development of automated visual surveillance and monitoring (VSAM) program, between 1997 and 1999, and airborne video surveillance (AVS) programs, from 1998 to 2002.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Currently, there is a major effort underway in the vision community to develop a fully-automated tracking surveillance system.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Automated video surveillance monitors people and vehicles in real-time within a busy environment.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Existing automated surveillance systems are based on the environment they are primarily designed to observe, i.e., indoor, outdoor or airborne, the number of sensors that the automated system can handle and the mobility of sensors, i.e., stationary camera vs. mobile camera.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The purpose of a surveillance system is to record properties and trajectories of objects in a given area, generate warnings or notify the designated authorities in case of occurrence of particular events.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] As demands for safety and mobility have grown and technological possibilities have multiplied, interest in automation has grown.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Seeking to accelerate the development and introduction of fully automated vehicles and highways, the U.S.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Congress authorized more than $650 million over six years for intelligent transport systems (ITS) and demonstration projects in the 1991 *Intermodal Surface Transportation Efficiency Act* (ISTEA).
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Full automation commonly defined as requiring no control or very limited control by the driver; such automation would be accomplished through a combination of sensor, computer, and communications systems in vehicles and along the roadway.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Fully automated driving would, in theory, allow closer vehicle spacing and higher speeds, which could enhance traffic capacity in places where additional road building is physically impossible, politically unacceptable, or prohibitively expensive.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Automated controls also might enhance road safety by reducing the opportunity for driver error, which causes a large share of motor vehicle crashes.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Other potential benefits include improved air quality (as a result of more-efficient traffic flows), increased fuel economy, and spin-off technologies generated during research and development related to automated highway systems.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Automated waste collection trucks prevent the need for as many workers as well as easing the level of labor required to provide the service.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Business process automation (BPA) is the technology-enabled automation of complex business processes.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] It can help to streamline a business for simplicity, achieve digital transformation, increase service quality, improve service delivery or contain costs.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] BPA consists of integrating applications, restructuring labor resources and using software applications throughout the organization.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Robotic process automation (RPA; or RPAAI for self-guided RPA 2.0) is an emerging field within BPA and uses AI.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] BPAs can be implemented in a number of business areas including recruitment, marketing, sales and workflow.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Home automation (also called **domotics**) designates an emerging practice of increased automation of household appliances and features in residential dwellings, particularly through electronic means that allow for things impracticable, overly expensive or simply not possible in recent past decades.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The rise in the usage of home automation solutions has taken a turn reflecting the increased dependency of people on such automation solutions.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] However, the increased comfort that gets added through these automation solutions is remarkable.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Automation is essential for many scientific and clinical applications.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Therefore, automation has been extensively employed in laboratories.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] From as early as 1980 fully automated laboratories have already been working.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] However, automation has not become widespread in laboratories due to its high cost.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] This may change with the ability of integrating low-cost devices with standard laboratory equipment.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Autosamplers are common devices used in laboratory automation.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Logistics automation is the application of computer software or automated machinery to improve the efficiency of logistics operations.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Typically this refers to operations within a warehouse or distribution center, with broader tasks undertaken by supply chain engineering systems and enterprise resource planning systems.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Industrial automation deals primarily with the automation of manufacturing, quality control, and material handling processes.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] General-purpose controllers for industrial processes include programmable logic controllers, stand-alone I/O modules, and computers.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Industrial automation is to replace the human action and manual command-response activities with the use of mechanized equipment and logical programming commands.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] One trend is increased use of machine vision to provide automatic inspection and robot guidance functions, another is a continuing increase in the use of robots.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Industrial automation is simply required in industries.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The rise of industrial automation is directly tied to the "Fourth Industrial Revolution", which is better known now as Industry 4.0.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Originating from Germany, Industry 4.0 encompasses numerous devices, concepts, and machines, as well as the advancement of the industrial internet of things (IIoT).
[src:applescript/automation-p01] An "Internet of Things is a seamless integration of diverse physical objects in the Internet through a virtual representation".
[src:applescript/automation-p01] These new advancements have drawn attention to the world of automation and have shown ways for it to increase productivity and efficiency in machinery and manufacturing facilities.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Industry 4.0 works with the IIoT and software/hardware to connect in a way that (through communication technologies) add enhancements and improve manufacturing processes.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Being able to create more advanced manufacturing is now possible with these new technologies.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] It opens up an improved manufacturing platform.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Implementation of systems such as SCADA is an example of software that takes place in industrial automation today.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] SCADA is a supervisory data collection software, just one of the many used in industrial automation.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Industry 4.0 covers many areas in manufacturing.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Industrial robotics is a sub-branch in industrial automation that aids in various manufacturing processes.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Such manufacturing processes include machining, welding, painting, assembling and material handling to name a few.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Industrial robots use various mechanical, electrical as well as software systems to allow for high precision, accuracy and speed that far exceed any human performance.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The birth of industrial robots came shortly after World War II as the U.S. saw the need for a quicker way to produce industrial and consumer goods.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Servos, digital logic and solid-state electronics allowed engineers to build better and faster systems and over time these systems were improved and revised to the point where a single robot is capable of running 24 hours a day with little or no maintenance.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] In 1997, there were 700,000 industrial robots in use, the number has risen to 1.8M in 2017 In recent years, AI with robotics is also used in creating an automatic labeling solution, using robotic arms as the automatic label applicator, and AI for learning and detecting the products to be labelled.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Industrial automation incorporates programmable logic controllers in the manufacturing process.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) use a processing system which allows for variation of controls of inputs and outputs using simple programming.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] PLCs make use of programmable memory, storing instructions and functions like logic, sequencing, timing, counting, etc.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Using a logic-based language, a PLC can receive a variety of inputs and return a variety of logical outputs, the input devices being sensors and output devices being motors, valves, etc.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] PLCs are similar to computers, however, while computers are optimized for calculations, PLCs are optimized for control tasks and use in industrial environments.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] They are built so that only basic logic-based programming knowledge is needed and to handle vibrations, high temperatures, humidity, and noise.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The greatest advantage PLCs offer is their flexibility.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] With the same basic controllers, a PLC can operate a range of different control systems.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] PLCs make it unnecessary to rewire a system to change the control system.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] This flexibility leads to a cost-effective system for complex and varied control systems.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] PLCs can range from small "building brick" devices with tens of I/O in a housing integral with the processor, to large rack-mounted modular devices with a count of thousands of I/O, and which are often networked to other PLC and SCADA systems.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] They can be designed for multiple arrangements of digital and analog inputs and outputs (I/O), extended temperature ranges, immunity to electrical noise, and resistance to vibration and impact.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Programs to control machine operation are typically stored in battery-backed-up or non-volatile memory.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] It was from the automotive industry in the United States that the PLC was born.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Before the PLC, control, sequencing, and safety interlock logic for manufacturing automobiles was mainly composed of relays, cam timers, drum sequencers, and dedicated closed-loop controllers.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Since these could number in the hundreds or even thousands, the process for updating such facilities for the yearly model change-over was very time-consuming and expensive, as electricians needed to individually rewire the relays to change their operational characteristics.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] When digital computers became available, being general-purpose programmable devices, they were soon applied to control sequential and combinatorial logic in industrial processes.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] However, these early computers required specialist programmers and stringent operating environmental control for temperature, cleanliness, and power quality.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] To meet these challenges, the PLC was developed with several key attributes.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] It would tolerate the shop-floor environment, it would support discrete (bit-form) input and output in an easily extensible manner, it would not require years of training to use, and it would permit its operation to be monitored.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Since many industrial processes have timescales easily addressed by millisecond response times, modern (fast, small, reliable) electronics greatly facilitate building reliable controllers, and performance could be traded off for reliability.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Agent-assisted automation refers to automation used by call center agents to handle customer inquiries.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The key benefit of agent-assisted automation is compliance and error-proofing.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] Agents are sometimes not fully trained or they forget or ignore key steps in the process.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] The use of automation ensures that what is supposed to happen on the call actually does, every time.
[src:applescript/automation-p01] There are two basic types: desktop automation and automated voice solutions.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] Fundamentally, there are two types of control loop: *open-loop control* (feedforward), and *closed-loop control* (feedback).
[src:applescript/automation-p02] One of the simplest types of control is *on-off* control.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] An example is a thermostat used on household appliances which either open or close an electrical contact.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] Sequence control, in which a programmed sequence of *discrete* operations is performed, often based on system logic that involves system states.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] An elevator control system is an example of sequence control.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] A proportional–integral–derivative controller (PID controller) is a control loop feedback mechanism (controller) widely used in industrial control systems.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] The theoretical understanding and application date from the 1920s, and they are implemented in nearly all analog control systems; originally in mechanical controllers, and then using discrete electronics and latterly in industrial process computers.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] Sequential control may be either to a fixed sequence or to a logical one that will perform different actions depending on various system states.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] An example of an adjustable but otherwise fixed sequence is a timer on a lawn sprinkler.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] States refer to the various conditions that can occur in a use or sequence scenario of the system.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] An example is an elevator, which uses logic based on the system state to perform certain actions in response to its state and operator input.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] For example, if the operator presses the floor n button, the system will respond depending on whether the elevator is stopped or moving, going up or down, or if the door is open or closed, and other conditions.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] Early development of sequential control was relay logic, by which electrical relays engage electrical contacts which either start or interrupt power to a device.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] Relays were first used in telegraph networks before being developed for controlling other devices, such as when starting and stopping industrial-sized electric motors or opening and closing solenoid valves.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] Using relays for control purposes allowed event-driven control, where actions could be triggered out of sequence, in response to external events.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] These were more flexible in their response than the rigid single-sequence cam timers.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] More complicated examples involved maintaining safe sequences for devices such as swing bridge controls, where a lock bolt needed to be disengaged before the bridge could be moved, and the lock bolt could not be released until the safety gates had already been closed.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] The total number of relays and cam timers can number into the hundreds or even thousands in some factories.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] Early programming techniques and languages were needed to make such systems manageable, one of the first being ladder logic, where diagrams of the interconnected relays resembled the rungs of a ladder.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] Special computers called programmable logic controllers were later designed to replace these collections of hardware with a single, more easily re-programmed unit.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] In a typical hard-wired motor start and stop circuit (called a *control circuit*) a motor is started by pushing a "Start" or "Run" button that activates a pair of electrical relays.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] The "lock-in" relay locks in contacts that keep the control circuit energized when the push-button is released.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] (The start button is a normally open contact and the stop button is a normally closed contact.) Another relay energizes a switch that powers the device that throws the motor starter switch (three sets of contacts for three-phase industrial power) in the main power circuit.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] Large motors use high voltage and experience high in-rush current, making speed important in making and breaking contact.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] This can be dangerous for personnel and property with manual switches.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] The "lock-in" contacts in the start circuit and the main power contacts for the motor are held engaged by their respective electromagnets until a "stop" or "off" button is pressed, which de-energizes the lock in relay.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] Commonly interlocks are added to a control circuit.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] Suppose that the motor in the example is powering machinery that has a critical need for lubrication.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] In this case, an interlock could be added to ensure that the oil pump is running before the motor starts.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] Timers, limit switches, and electric eyes are other common elements in control circuits.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] Solenoid valves are widely used on compressed air or hydraulic fluid for powering actuators on mechanical components.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] Computers can perform both sequential control and feedback control, and typically a single computer will do both in an industrial application.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) are a type of special-purpose microprocessor that replaced many hardware components such as timers and drum sequencers used in relay logic–type systems.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] General-purpose process control computers have increasingly replaced stand-alone controllers, with a single computer able to perform the operations of hundreds of controllers.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] Process control computers can process data from a network of PLCs, instruments, and controllers to implement typical (such as PID) control of many individual variables or, in some cases, to implement complex control algorithms using multiple inputs and mathematical manipulations.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] They can also analyze data and create real-time graphical displays for operators and run reports for operators, engineers, and management.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] Control of an automated teller machine (ATM) is an example of an interactive process in which a computer will perform a logic-derived response to a user selection based on information retrieved from a networked database.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] The ATM process has similarities with other online transaction processes.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] The different logical responses are called *scenarios*.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] Such processes are typically designed with the aid of use cases and flowcharts, which guide the writing of the software code.
[src:applescript/automation-p02] The earliest feedback control mechanism was the water clock invented by Greek engineer Ctesibius (285–222 BC).
[src:applescript/scripting-language] In computing, a **script** is a relatively short and simple set of instructions that typically automate an otherwise manual process.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] The act of writing a script is called **scripting**.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] A **scripting language** or **script language** is a programming language that is used for scripting.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Originally, scripting was limited to automating shells in operating systems, and languages were relatively simple.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Today, scripting is more pervasive and some scripting languages include modern features that allow them to be used to develop application software also.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] A scripting language can be a general-purpose programming language or a domain-specific language for a given environment.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] When embedded in an application, it may be called an *extension language*.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] A scripting language is sometimes referred to as very high-level programming language if it operates at a high level of abstraction, or as a *control language*, especially for job control languages on mainframe computers.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] The term *scripting language* is sometimes used in a wider sense, to refer to dynamic high-level programming languages in general.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Some are strictly interpreted languages, while others use a form of compilation.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] In this context, the term *script* refers to a small program in such a language.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Typically, a script is contained in a single file, and no larger than a few thousand lines of code.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] The scope of scripting languages ranges from small to large, and from highly domain-specific language to general-purpose programming languages.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] A language may start as small and highly domain-specific and later develop into a portable and general-purpose language; conversely, a general-purpose language may later develop special domain-specific dialects.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Script is a subjective characterization that generally includes the following attributes.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] A script is usually not compiled, at least not its usual meaning.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Generally, they are interpreted directly from source code, or from bytecode, or run as native after just-in-time compilation.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] A script is generally relatively short and simple.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] As there is no limit on size or complexity, script is subjective.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] A few lines of code without branching is probably considered a script.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] A codebase of multiple files, that performs sophisticated user or hardware interface or complicated algorithms or multiprogramming is probably not considered a script.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] A script usually automates a task that would otherwise be performed by a person in a more manual way.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] A language that is primarily intended for scripting generally has limited capabilities compared to a general-purpose language.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] A scripting language may lack the functionality to write complex applications.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Typically, a script starts executing at the first line of code whereas an application typically starts at a special point in the code called the entry point.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] For example, Java is not script-like since an application starts at the function named `main` which need not be at the top of the code.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] The following code starts at `main`, then calls `printHelloWorld` which prints "Hello World".
[src:applescript/scripting-language] In contrast, the following Python code prints "Hello World" without the `main` function or other syntax such as a class definition required by Java.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Scripts are often created or modified by the person executing them, but they are also often distributed, such as when large portions of games are written in a scripting language, notably the Google Chrome T-rex game.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Early mainframe computers (in the 1950s) were non-interactive, instead using batch processing.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] IBM's Job Control Language (JCL) is the archetype of languages used to control batch processing.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] The first interactive shells were developed in the 1960s to enable remote operation of the first time-sharing systems, and these used shell scripts, which controlled running computer programs within a computer program, the shell.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Calvin Mooers in his TRAC language is generally credited with inventing *command substitution*, the ability to embed commands in scripts that, when interpreted, insert a character string into the script.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Louis Pouzin wrote an early processor for command scripts called RUNCOM for CTSS around 1964.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Stuart Madnick at MIT wrote a scripting language for IBM's CP/CMS in 1966.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] He originally called this processor COMMAND, later named EXEC.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Multics included an offshoot of CTSS RUNCOM, also called RUNCOM.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] EXEC was eventually replaced by EXEC 2 and Rexx.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Languages such as Tcl and Lua were specifically designed as general-purpose scripting languages that could be embedded in any application.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Other languages such as Visual Basic for Applications (VBA) provided strong integration with the automation facilities of an underlying system.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Embedding of such general-purpose scripting languages instead of developing a new language for each application also had obvious benefits, relieving the application developer of the need to code a language translator from scratch and allowing the user to apply skills learned elsewhere.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Some software incorporates several different scripting languages.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Modern web browsers typically provide a language for writing extensions to the browser itself, and several standard embedded languages for controlling the browser, including JavaScript (a dialect of ECMAScript) or XUL.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Scripting languages can be categorized into several different types, with a considerable degree of overlap among the types.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Scripting is often contrasted with system programming, as in Ousterhout's dichotomy or "programming in the large and programming in the small".
[src:applescript/scripting-language] In this view, scripting is glue code, connecting software components, and a language specialized for this purpose is a *glue language*.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Pipelines and shell scripting are archetypal examples of glue languages, and Perl was initially developed to fill this same role.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Web development can be considered a use of glue languages, interfacing between a database and web server.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] But if a substantial amount of logic is written in script, it is better characterized as simply another software component, not "glue".
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Macro languages exposed to operating system or application components can serve as glue languages.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] These include Visual Basic for Applications, WordBasic, LotusScript, CorelScript, Hummingbird Basic, QuickScript, Rexx, SaxBasic, and WinWrap Basic.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Other tools like AWK can also be considered glue languages, as can any language implemented by a Windows Script Host engine (VBScript, JScript and VBA by default in Windows and third-party engines including implementations of Rexx, Perl, Tcl, Python, XSLT, Ruby, Modern Pascal, Delphi, and C).
[src:applescript/scripting-language] A majority of applications can access and use operating system components via the object models or its own functions.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Depending upon the OS version, WSH and the default script engines (VBScript and JScript) are available.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Programmable calculators can be programmed in glue languages in three ways.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] For example, the Texas Instruments TI-92, by factory default can be programmed with a command script language.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Inclusion of the scripting and glue language Lua in the TI-NSpire series of calculators could be seen as a successor to this.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] The primary on-board high-level programming languages of most graphing calculators (most often Basic variants, sometimes Lisp derivatives, and more uncommonly, C derivatives) in many cases can glue together calculator functions—such as graphs, lists, matrices, etc.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Third-party implementations of more comprehensive Basic version that may be closer to variants listed as glue languages in this article are available—and attempts to implement Perl, Rexx, or various operating system shells on the TI and HP graphing calculators are also mentioned.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] A number of text editors support macros written either using a macro language built into the editor, e.g., The SemWare Editor (TSE), vi improved (VIM), or using an external implementation, e.g., XEDIT, or both, e.g., KEDIT.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Sometimes text editors and edit macros are used under the covers to provide other applications, e.g., FILELIST and RDRLIST in CMS .
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Many of these languages' interpreters double as command-line interpreters such as the Unix shell or the MS-DOS `COMMAND.COM`.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Others, such as AppleScript offer the use of English-like commands to build scripts.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] With the advent of graphical user interfaces, a specialized kind of scripting language emerged for controlling a computer.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] These languages interact with the same graphic windows, menus, buttons, and so on, that a human user would.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] They do this by simulating the actions of a user.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] These languages are typically used to automate user actions.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Such languages are also called *macros* when control is through simulated key presses or mouse clicks, and tapping or pressing on a touch-activated screen.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] These languages could in principle be used to control any GUI application, but in practice their use is limited because they need support from the application and from the operating system.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] There are a few exceptions to this limit.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Some GUI scripting languages are based on recognizing graphical objects from their display screen pixels.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] These GUI scripting languages do not depend on support from the operating system or application.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] When the GUI provides the appropriate interfaces, as in the IBM Workplace Shell, a generic scripting language, e.g., Object REXX, can be used to write GUI scripts.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Likewise, many computer game systems use a custom scripting language to express the programmed actions of non-player characters and the game environment.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Languages of this sort are designed for a single application; while they may superficially resemble a specific general-purpose language (e.g., QuakeC, modeled after C), they have custom features that distinguish them.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Emacs Lisp, while a fully formed and capable dialect of Lisp, contains many special features that make it most useful for extending the editing functions of Emacs.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] An application-specific scripting language can be viewed as a domain-specific programming language specialized to one application.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] A number of languages have been designed for the purpose of replacing application-specific scripting languages by being embeddable in application programs.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] The application programmer (working in C or another systems language) includes "hooks" where the scripting language can control the application.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] These languages may be technically equivalent to an application-specific extension language but when an application embeds a "common" language, the user gets the advantage of being able to transfer skills from application to application.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] A more generic alternative is simply to provide a library (often a C library) that a general-purpose language can use to control the application, without modifying the language for the specific domain.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] JavaScript began as, and still is mostly, a language for scripting inside web browsers.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] However, the standardizing of the language as ECMAScript has made it popular as a general-purpose embeddable language.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] The Mozilla implementation SpiderMonkey is embedded in several environments such as the Yahoo Widgets Engine,and applications such as the Adobe products Flash (ActionScript) and Acrobat (for scripting PDF files).
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Tcl was created as an extension language but has come to be used more often as a general-purpose language in roles similar to Python, Perl, and Ruby.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] In contrast, Rexx was created as a job control language, but is widely used as an extension language and a general-purpose language.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Perl is a general-purpose language, but had the Oraperl (1990) dialect, consisting of a Perl 4 binary with Oracle Call Interface compiled in.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] This has however since been replaced by a library (Perl Module), DBD::Oracle.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Other complex and task-oriented applications may incorporate and expose an embedded programming language to allow their users more control and give them more functionality than can be available through a user interface, no matter how sophisticated.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] For example, Autodesk Maya 3D authoring tools embed the Maya Embedded Language, or Blender which uses Python to fill this role.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] Some other types of applications that need faster feature addition or tweak-and-run cycles (e.g. game engines) also use an embedded language.
[src:applescript/scripting-language] During the development, this allows them to prototype features faster and tweak more freely, without the need for the user to have intimate knowledge of the inner workings of the application or to rebuild it after each tweak (which can take a significant amount of time).
[src:applescript/scripting-language] The scripting languages used for this purpose range from the more common and more famous Lua and Python to lesser-known ones such as AngelScript and Squirrel.
